title: Psychology Study Group, Task 3 Auto - Function of Behavior
authors: EDUC 3100 Assessment Module

~~~~

Introduction [id=fba2_intro_section]
------------

::fba2_introduction [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="View Introduction"]

Annie: Thanks again for your help with my roommate's dilemma with Johnny, the kid she babysits. She has been trying all kinds of positive reinforcement techniques to get him to go to bed, but she says they aren't working out like she thought they would. [face=fear]

JJ: Oh no! That must be hard. What's going on?

Annie: She has been rewarding him for going to his room when she asks by letting him play with his favorite toys before bed.

Lin: Yep, that sounds like positive reinforcement. What's the issue?

Annie: After a while, she tells him to put away his toys in a box in his room, which he does.

JJ: Great! Glad to hear he's finally following some directions! [face=smile]

Annie: Then, she tells him to get into bed, but like always, he runs away from the room laughing whenever "bed" is mentioned.

Lin: Well, does he eventually go to bed? [face=concerned]

Annie: Well, yeah, but not without a fight. After he runs away, my roommate chases after him and keeps nagging on him to go to bed. I think he eventually gets tired and goes to bed, but my roommate is left feeling tired and frustrated, just like before.

JJ: Yikes. Looks like it's time to go back to the drawing board! [face=concerned]

Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_intro]
---------------------

Lin: One of the things we learned in class was that whenever you need to intervene with a behavior, the intervention must address the function of the behavior.

Annie: What in the world does that mean? Function?? [face=hectic]

JJ: I don't remember at all. Let's ask AI.

Lin: Wait -- I remember our T.A. telling us that it's better to try to actively remember something than to just passively read it. You understand it better that way.

JJ: Well, it's worth a try if one of you remembers better than I do. But I'll write a prompt to get AI to evaluate your answer. That way we can see if we missed something! [face=explaining]

::fba2_ai_function_def [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Define Function of Behavior"]

--- wait @fba2_ai_function_response.value ---

Annie: Oh, that's helpful! So we need to figure out WHY Johnny is running away at bedtime. [face=smile]

Introducing Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_concepts]
---------------------------------

::fba2_function_notes [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="View Lin's Notes"]

Lin: Here are my notes from class. The four main functions of behavior are attention, escape, access to preferred activity/object, and sensory.

JJ: My notes say that the function always refers to a type of reinforcement, positive or negative.

Annie: Positive and negative reinforcement! We went over that last time...

Lin: I took a picture of a couple of examples that our TA Lianne wrote down on the board that would help me remember...

Review of Previously Learned Concepts [id=fba2_reinforcement_review_section]
--------------------------------------

Lin: Before we go further, let's make sure we remember the basics. Let's work through a few of these until we get, say, 3 in a row right. [face=serious]

JJ: Good idea. That way we know we're not just guessing! [face=smile]

::fba2_reinforcement_review [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Review Reinforcement Concepts"]

--- wait @fba2_reinforcement_mastery.completed ---

Teaching Function of Behavior [id=fba2_function_teaching]
------------------------------

JJ: Whew, thank you for the refresher. I needed that. [face=relieved]

Lin: Me too. Lianne also said a couple of other things during our last class. She said that if the function is for attention or tangibles, it usually involves positive reinforcement. If the function is escape, it typically involves negative reinforcement. And for sensory, it can be either one.

Annie: I think it would really help my brain if we put all these concepts together. I think AI would help here.

JJ: OK, I tried writing a prompt. Here's my first attempt -- "You are a helpful psychology teaching assistant. Create a chart showing the four functions of behavior with examples of how each relates to positive and negative reinforcement." [face=explaining]

Lin: Have you tried it?

JJ: I did. The results looked good on the surface, but when I worked through them carefully, I discovered it would fill in cells that really shouldn't be filled in, with subtly misleading examples. I had to tweak the prompt several times before the results were consistently correct. [face=concerned]

Annie: So what was your final prompt? [face=surprised]

JJ: Basically, I had to spell out which combinations are valid and tell it to leave incompatible cells blank. It was like the AI was so eager to follow directions that it fudged things to fill in all of the cells otherwise. [face=smile]

::fba2_ai_function_chart [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Create Function Chart with AI"]

--- wait @fba2_ai_chart_response.value ---

Lin: That chart makes things so much clearer! [face=smile]

JJ: Especially because it leaves two cells blank. Escape is the removal of something unwanted, so it doesn't combine with positive reinforcement, which is adding something. And access to tangibles is about getting something, so it doesn't combine with negative reinforcement, which is about removing something. [face=explaining]

Annie: Good catch, JJ! But we won't really **learn** what the chart is telling us unless we try ourselves.

Your Turn: Own Examples [id=fba2_own_examples_section]
------------------------

Annie: Let's each come up with our own examples for each function. That way we'll really know if we understand the chart.

Lin: For each function, try to think of a situation that involves positive reinforcement, and another that involves negative reinforcement. Some combinations might be tricky!

::fba2_own_examples_attention [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Your Examples: Attention"]

--- wait @fba2_pos_reinforcement_attention.value && @fba2_neg_reinforcement_attention.value ---

::fba2_own_examples_escape [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Your Examples: Escape"]

--- wait @fba2_pos_reinforcement_escape.value && @fba2_neg_reinforcement_escape.value ---

::fba2_own_examples_access [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Your Examples: Access"]

--- wait @fba2_pos_reinforcement_access.value && @fba2_neg_reinforcement_access.value ---

::fba2_own_examples_sensory [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Your Examples: Sensory"]

--- wait @fba2_pos_reinforcement_sensory.value && @fba2_neg_reinforcement_sensory.value ---

Annie: Some of those were really hard! Did anyone else have trouble with escape and positive reinforcement?

JJ: Yes! That's because those combinations don't actually work -- which is exactly what the blank cells in the chart were telling us.

JJ: But didn't we learn about punishment too?

Lin: Yeah, I thought punishment could be a function too.

Check for Understanding - Punishment [id=fba2_punishment_check]
--------------------------------------

Annie: Hmm, before we look up the answer, what do you all think? Why might punishment NOT be listed as a function of behavior? [face=thinking]

::fba2_predict_punishment [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Predict: Why Not Punishment?"]

--- wait @fba2_punishment_confidence.value ---

Annie: That makes sense! Functions are about what we GAIN from the behavior, not what we're trying to avoid. [face=smile]

Practice with Functions [id=fba2_function_practice]
------------------------

JJ: This is starting to make sense, but I think I need more practice.

Lin: Me too.

Annie: I asked AI to come up with some examples about the functions of behaviors for us to use to test our knowledge. Let's try them together.

::fba2_function_sorting [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Practice: Identify Functions"]

