Intervention Planning [id=fba2_intervention_section]
----------------------

JJ: Okay, so now we need to figure out an intervention now that we know the function of the behavior of running away from his room at bedtime is escape.

Lin: Right, and here's what my textbook says about escape.

::fba2_textbook_escape [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Read Textbook on Escape"]

Annie: We sure focused a lot on consequences in our last project, but we did not focus much on antecedents.

Checking Intervention Understanding [id=fba2_intervention_check]
------------------------------------

::fba2_intervention_strategies [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar3auto label="Sort Intervention Strategies"]

Lin: Take a look at what my Child Development course's textbook says about generating interventions. The problem behavior we're talking about is "not going to bed on time."

JJ: Maybe we should consider both antecedents and consequences. I think it would be better to break it up -- let's think about antecedent strategies first, then consequence strategies separately. Otherwise we'll get too many possibilities at once. [face=explaining]

--- wait @fba2_escape_strategies_done.value ---

Annie: I think I've got the hang of this now!! [face=smile]

Annie: But not all the strategies we're finding are focused on addressing ESCAPE specifically. We should narrow down to strategies that prevent or discourage escape-oriented behavior.

JJ: Great point. Let's ask AI to help us think of even more interventions, this time focused specifically on escape as the function of behavior. Then we'll create our new behavior modification plan!

Annie: My roommate is going to be so happy!

